    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1260960722" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1260960722" />
    <a title="Anne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42321-anne"><img alt="Anne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388463861p2/42321.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1260960722?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anne" href="/user/show/42321-anne">Anne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1260960722" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2662875671891762849">I&apos;m sufficiently obsessed with this series that I&apos;m probably never going to give less than 3 stars, but I thought this one was a little overwrought and complicated. Too many new characters, most of whom were going by an assumed name, and the solution to the central mystery hearkened back to something that was mentioned in the first few pages...when I wasn&apos;t paying attention.<br/><br/>That said, I am constantly amazed by Ellis Peters&apos; exhaustive knowledge of this period. Even though certain tropes do come </span>
  <span id="freeText2662875671891762849" style="display:none">I'm sufficiently obsessed with this series that I'm probably never going to give less than 3 stars, but I thought this one was a little overwrought and complicated. Too many new characters, most of whom were going by an assumed name, and the solution to the central mystery hearkened back to something that was mentioned in the first few pages...when I wasn't paying attention.<br /><br />That said, I am constantly amazed by Ellis Peters' exhaustive knowledge of this period. Even though certain tropes do come up over and over again (they're whodunits, so by nature somewhat formulaic), every book has a unique mystery and addresses a facet of medieval or monastic life that never occurred to me.<br /><br />(P.S. The copy of The Hermit of Eyton Forest that I bought on E-Bay was published by a different publisher than the rest of the Cadfael books I have, and it didn't list which number in the series it was. As it turns out, had I bothered to check, I would have read this one ages ago, before The Confession of Brother Haluin. Just saying.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="2662875671891762849" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1260960722">
